          "cookies": [],
          "content": {
            "size": 5952,
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "text": "{\"thread_id\":\"b25c2017-6218-4554-8cba-524b8b2e67a1\",\"thread_name\":\"Duas to Make Ramadan Charity Meaningful\",\"source\":\"web\",\"created_at\":\"2026-03-19T05:29:32.175Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-03-19T05:30:00.210Z\",\"messages\":[{\"id\":\"73e294a9-1726-4145-9a9b-e6aeba73b5b0\",\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Can you suggest some duas for making charitable acts during Ramadan more meaningful?\",\"agent_name\":null,\"source\":\"web\",\"created_at\":\"2026-03-19T05:29:33.166Z\"},{\"id\":\"968ef771-2457-44bf-98b6-e14701b4e1a6\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Giving charity (Sadaqah) during Ramadan is a deeply spiritual act, following the example of the Prophet (ﷺ), who was described as being more generous than a \\\"fast wind\\\" during this blessed month [4]. To make these acts more meaningful, one should focus on the intention (*niyyah*), the source of the wealth, and the supplication for its acceptance.\\n\\nHere are the most recommended supplications and principles based on the Quran and Sunnah:\\n\\n### 1. The Supplication for Acceptance\\nThe most profound dua to make when performing any good deed, including charity, is the one used by Prophet Ibrahim (AS) and Prophet Ismail (AS) while they were performing the monumental task of building the Kaaba. Despite the greatness of their deed, they remained humble and asked for acceptance:\\n\\n**رَبَّنَا تَقَبَّلْ مِنَّآ ۖ إِنَّكَ أَنتَ ٱلسَّمِيعُ ٱلْعَلِيمُ**\\n*\\\"Our Lord! Accept [this] from us. You are indeed the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.\\\"* [1]\\n\\nScholars like Wuhaib ibn al-Ward used to weep when reciting this verse, reflecting on the fact that even the \\\"Friend of Allah\\\" (Ibrahim AS) was fearful that his deed might not be accepted [6]. Using this dua ensures your heart is focused on Allah’s acceptance rather than self-praise.\\n\\n### 2. Seeking Sincerity (Ikhlas)\\nCharity becomes \\\"meaningful\\\" when it is done solely for the sake of Allah. You can make a personal supplication in any language, or use this general prophetic sentiment:\\n\\n**اللهم اجعل عملي كله صالحاً، واجعله لوجهك خالصاً، ولا تجعل لأحد فيه شيئاً**\\n*\\\"O Allah, make all of my deeds righteous, and make them purely for Your sake, and do not let there be any share for anyone else in them.\\\"*\\n\\n### 3. Reflecting on the Prophet’s Generosity\\nTo gain the full spirit of Ramadan, remember the description of the Prophet (ﷺ) during this month. Narrated Ibn Abbas (RA):\\n> \\\"The Prophet (ﷺ) was the most generous of all the people, and he used to become more generous in Ramadan when Gabriel met him... Allah's Messenger (ﷺ) then used to be more generous than the fast wind.\\\" [4]\\n\\nWhen giving, you can pray to be among those who emulate this \\\"fast wind\\\" in doing good—acting quickly, broadly, and without hesitation.\\n\\n### 4. Giving from the \\\"Best\\\" and \\\"Pure\\\"\\nMeaningful charity is that which comes from a lawful and good source. The Prophet (ﷺ) taught that Allah is *Tayyib* (Pure/Good) and only accepts that which is pure [7]. Supplicate that Allah purifies your wealth:\\n\\n**اللَّهُمَّ اكْفِنِي بِحَلَالِكَ عَنْ حَرَامِكَ وَأَغْنِنِي بِفَضْلِكَ عَمَّنْ سِوَاكَ**\\n*\\\"O Allah, suffice me with what is lawful instead of what is forbidden, and make me independent of all others through Your grace.\\\"*\\n\\n### Key Etiquettes for a More Meaningful Charity:\\n1.  **Secrecy:** While public charity is permissible, giving in secret is highly praised as it protects the heart from showing off (*Riya*).\\n2.  **Dignity of the Recipient:** Avoid reminding the person of your favor (*Mann*), as this nullifies the reward.\\n3.  **Consistency:** The Prophet (ﷺ) said the most beloved deeds to Allah are those done consistently, even if they are small.\\n\\n**Citations**:\\n[1] Quran 2:127\\n    Arabic: وَإِذْ يَرْفَعُ إِبْرَٰهِـۧمُ ٱلْقَوَاعِدَ مِنَ ٱلْبَيْتِ وَإِسْمَـٰعِيلُ رَبَّنَا تَقَبَّلْ مِنَّآ ۖ إِنَّكَ أَنتَ ٱلسَّمِيعُ ٱلْعَلِيمُ\\n    English: And ˹remember˺ when Abraham raised the foundation of the House with Ishmael, ˹both praying,˺ “Our Lord! Accept ˹this˺ from us. You are indeed the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.\\\"\\n\\n[4] Sahih Bukhari - Chapter 30: Fasting, Hadith 1902\\n    Arabic: كَانَ رَسُولُ اللَّهِ صلى الله عليه وسلم أَجْوَدَ النَّاسِ، وَكَانَ أَجْوَدَ مَا يَكُونُ فِي رَمَضَانَ... فَلَرَسُولُ اللَّهِ صلى الله عليه وسلم أَجْوَدُ بِالْخَيْرِ مِنَ الرِّيحِ الْمُرْسَلَةِ\\n    English: The Prophet (ﷺ) was the most generous amongst the people, and he used to be more so in the month of Ramadan... The Prophet (ﷺ) used to be more generous than a fast wind (which causes rain and welfare).\\n\\n[6] Tafsir Encyclopedia, Volume 3, Page 66 (Effect of Quran 2:127 on scholars)\\n    Arabic: عن وهيب بن الورد... ترفع قوائم بيت الرحمن وأنت مشفق أن لا يقبل منك\\n    English: Narrated from Wuhaib ibn al-Ward... (Upon reading 2:127) he cried and said: \\\"O Khalil of Allah, you raise the foundations of the House of the Rahman while you are afraid it might not be accepted from you.\\\"\\n\\n[7] Tafsir Encyclopedia, Volume 10, Page 624 (Relating to Quran 9:104)\\n    Arabic: لا يقبل الله إلا طيبا... فيضعها في حق؛ إلا كانت كأنما يضعها في يد الرحمن، فيربيها له\\n    English: Allah does not accept except what is good (pure)... if one gives it to a rightful cause, it is as if he puts it in the Hand of the Most Merciful, who nurtures it for him.\",\"agent_name\":\"facilitator\",\"source\":\"web\",\"created_at\":\"2026-03-19T05:30:00.223Z\"}]}"
          },
